  "text": "where α and β are the Dirac matrices, Λ ++ is an operator which projects to the positive energy solutions and V N (r i ) is the nuclear potential. Sandwiching the Hamiltonian with Λ ++ ensures that the effects of the negative energy continuum states are neglected in the calculations. Another approach, which is better suited for numerical computations, is to use the kinetically balanced finite basis sets [29] [30] [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . We use this method in the present work to generate the orbital basis sets. The last two terms, 1/r ij and g B (r ij ) are the Coulomb and Breit interactions, respectively. The later, Breit interaction, represents the inter-electron magnetic interactions and is given by",
